ItalicBold: 2
Text: ' "white", is the '
Begin Reference: diffuse reflection
k: null
Text: 'diffuse reflectivity'
End Reference: diffuse reflection
Text: ' or reflecting power of a surface. It is defined as the ratio of reflected radiation from the surface to incident radiation upon it. Being a '
Begin Reference: Dimensionless number
k: null
Text: 'dimensionless'
End Reference: Dimensionless number
Text: ' fraction, it may also be expressed as a percentage, and is measured on a scale from zero for no reflecting power of a perfectly black surface, to 1 for perfect reflection of a white surface.

Albedo depends on the '
Begin Reference: frequency
End Reference: frequency
Text: ' of the radiation. When quoted unqualified, it usually refers to some appropriate average across the spectrum of '
Begin Reference: visible light
End Reference: visible light
Text: '. In general, the albedo depends on the directional distribution of incoming radiation.  Exceptions are '
Begin Reference: Lambertian
End Reference: Lambertian
Text: ' surfaces, which scatter radiation in all directions according to a cosine function, so their albedo does not depend on the incident distribution. In practice, a '
Begin Reference: bidirectional reflectance distribution function
End Reference: bidirectional reflectance distribution function
Text: ' (BRDF) may be required to characterize the scattering properties of a surface accurately, although the albedo is a very useful first approximation.

The albedo is an important concept in '
Begin Reference: climatology
End Reference: climatology
Text: ' and '
Begin Reference: astronomy
End Reference: astronomy
Text: ', as well as in calculating '
Begin Reference: reflectivity
End Reference: reflectivity
Text: ' of surfaces in LEED sustainable rating systems for buildings, computer graphics and computer vision. The average overall albedo of Earth, its '
ItalicBold: 2
Text: 'planetary albedo'
ItalicBold: 2
Text: ', is 30 to 35%, because of the covering by clouds, but varies widely locally across the surface, depending on the geological and environmental features.'
