Section [1] White-sky and black-sky albedo
Text: '
It has been shown that for many applications involving terrestrial albedo, the albedo at a particular solar '
Begin Reference: Celestial coordinate system
k: null
Text: 'zenith angle'
End Reference: Celestial coordinate system
Text: ' '
Open Tag: math attributes: []
Text: '{\theta_i}'
Close Tag: math
Text: ' can reasonably be approximated by the proportionate sum of two terms: the directional-hemispherical reflectance at that solar zenith angle, '
Open Tag: math attributes: []
Text: '{\bar \alpha(\theta_i)}'
Close Tag: math
Text: ', and the bi-hemispherical reflectance, '
Open Tag: math attributes: []
Text: '\bar{ \bar \alpha}'
Close Tag: math
Text: ' the proportion concerned being defined as the proportion of diffuse illumination '
Open Tag: math attributes: []
Text: '{D}'
Close Tag: math
Text: '.

Albedo '
Open Tag: math attributes: []
Text: '{\alpha}'
Close Tag: math
Text: ' can then be given as:

:'
Open Tag: math attributes: []
Text: '{\alpha}= (1-D) \bar \alpha(\theta_i) + D \bar{ \bar \alpha}.'
Close Tag: math
Text: '

'
Begin Reference: Directional-hemispherical reflectance
End Reference: Directional-hemispherical reflectance
Text: ' is sometimes referred to as black-sky albedo and '
Begin Reference: bi-hemispherical reflectance
End Reference: bi-hemispherical reflectance
Text: ' as white sky albedo. These terms are important because they allow the albedo to be calculated for any given illumination conditions from a knowledge of the intrinsic properties of the surface.'
Inline Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'BlueskyAlbedo']
