Section [1] Trees
Text: '
Because trees tend to have a low albedo, removing forests would tend to increase albedo and thereby could produce localized climate cooling (ignoring the lost evaporative cooling effect of trees). '
Begin Reference: Cloud feedback
End Reference: Cloud feedback
Text: 's further complicate the issue. In seasonally snow-covered zones, winter albedos of treeless areas are 10% to 50% higher than nearby forested areas because snow does not cover the trees as readily. '
Begin Reference: Deciduous trees
End Reference: Deciduous trees
Text: ' have an albedo value of about 0.15 to 0.18 while '
Begin Reference: coniferous trees
End Reference: coniferous trees
Text: ' have a value of about 0.09 to 0.15.'
Inline Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'mmutrees']
Text: '

Studies by the '
Begin Reference: Hadley Centre
End Reference: Hadley Centre
Text: ' have investigated the relative (generally warming) effect of albedo change and (cooling) effect of '
Begin Reference: carbon sequestration
End Reference: carbon sequestration
Text: ' on planting forests. They found that new forests in tropical and midlatitude areas tended to cool; new forests in high latitudes (e.g. Siberia) were neutral or perhaps warming.'
Inline Tag: ref attributes: [name : 'Betts']
Text: '

'
Section [1] Snow
Text: '
Snow albedos can be as high as 0.9; this, however, is for the ideal example: fresh deep snow over a featureless landscape. Over '
Begin Reference: Antarctica
End Reference: Antarctica
Text: ' they average a little more than 0.8.  If a marginally snow-covered area warms, snow tends to melt, lowering the albedo, and hence leading to more snowmelt (the ice-albedo '
Begin Reference: positive feedback
End Reference: positive feedback
Text: '). '
Begin Reference: Cryoconite
End Reference: Cryoconite
Text: ', powdery windblown '
Begin Reference: dust
End Reference: dust
Text: ' containing soot, sometimes reduces albedo on glaciers and ice sheets.'
